00:15:39,304 --> 00:15:40,385
And so I'll jump right in.

369
00:15:41,085 --> 00:15:42,987
And the first tip, the first tip of the day

370
00:15:43,167 --> 00:15:44,227
is start with the why.

371
00:15:45,389 --> 00:15:48,177
When we talk about high performance on teams,

372
00:15:48,377 --> 00:15:49,841
we usually talk about motivation.

373
00:15:50,382 --> 00:15:51,846
So what drives motivation?

374
00:15:51,906 --> 00:15:54,152
What drives people to perform highly?

375
00:15:55,259 --> 00:15:57,681
And it's an interesting question.

376
00:15:57,701 --> 00:15:59,522
I remember when I was interviewing at Microsoft

377
00:15:59,542 --> 00:16:01,764
about like five years ago, I think,

378
00:16:02,665 --> 00:16:03,506
the interviewer asked me,

379
00:16:03,526 --> 00:16:06,048
like how do you motivate teams through crunch time?

380
00:16:07,069 --> 00:16:09,951
And I was just switching to production at the time

381
00:16:10,231 --> 00:16:11,352
and I thought about it and I'm like,

382
00:16:11,813 --> 00:16:14,955
well, I buy pizza and donuts

383
00:16:15,155 --> 00:16:16,316
and I hope they feel better about it.

384
00:16:17,357 --> 00:16:18,878
So my interview didn't go well.

385
00:16:20,276 --> 00:16:23,417
But my thinking evolved since then,

386
00:16:23,517 --> 00:16:27,679
and so I read the book by Daniel Pink about drive.

387
00:16:28,019 --> 00:16:31,120
And in that book he says there are three primary motivators,

388
00:16:31,260 --> 00:16:32,520
two primary drivers for motivation.

389
00:16:33,501 --> 00:16:37,402
And it's purpose, autonomy, and mastery.

390
00:16:37,642 --> 00:16:38,923
Purpose, autonomy, and mastery.

391
00:16:39,543 --> 00:16:40,964
And so the sense of purpose

392
00:16:41,364 --> 00:16:43,484
is probably the strongest way to motivate people.

393
00:16:44,345 --> 00:16:50,376
And the way I mean this is when you have a team comprised of individuals whose sense

394
00:16:50,416 --> 00:16:55,987
of their own internal purpose is aligned with your why for the team, it's a very powerful

395
00:16:56,007 --> 00:16:56,528
combination.

396
00:16:57,432 --> 00:16:59,292
I'll give you an example of how this works on my team.

397
00:16:59,772 --> 00:17:01,333
I'm heading a platform team.

398
00:17:02,133 --> 00:17:04,454
And we're doing stuff that's generally

399
00:17:04,494 --> 00:17:05,675
considered not very sexy.

400
00:17:05,755 --> 00:17:06,835
I personally think it's sexy.

401
00:17:06,855 --> 00:17:10,016
But it's like installers, patchers, servers,

402
00:17:10,456 --> 00:17:13,637
localization, all this stuff that is not the actual game

403
00:17:13,677 --> 00:17:14,118
development.

404
00:17:14,718 --> 00:17:18,121
And so when I try to motivate people to work on my team,

405
00:17:18,321 --> 00:17:19,423
it sometimes is hard.

406
00:17:20,223 --> 00:17:22,385
But I have this guy on my team, his name is Michael.

407
00:17:22,846 --> 00:17:25,549
And I talk to him about why he works on my team

408
00:17:25,609 --> 00:17:26,610
and he gave me this story.

409
00:17:27,130 --> 00:17:28,492
He actually used to be a teacher

410
00:17:29,012 --> 00:17:32,095
and he one day noticed a kid in his class.

411
00:17:33,036 --> 00:17:37,080
The kid was like super unhappy, he was very shy, very...

412
00:17:38,742 --> 00:17:40,784
Like, nobody would even talk to the kid.

413
00:17:41,785 --> 00:17:43,787
And Michael decided to help him.

414
00:17:44,468 --> 00:17:46,651
So he sat down with the kid, and for the next couple of

415
00:17:46,711 --> 00:17:48,613
weeks, he showed him how to make a game.

416
00:17:48,973 --> 00:17:50,355
So they made this little game together.

417
00:17:50,375 --> 00:17:53,558
And then this kid brought it and showed it to the classmates.

418
00:17:54,319 --> 00:17:59,307
Overnight, he became from like a total pariah, somebody who nobody would even talk to,

419
00:17:59,667 --> 00:18:01,450
to the most popular kid in the class.

420
00:18:02,111 --> 00:18:08,360
And so Michael changed this kid's life by helping him with making this game.

421
00:18:09,221 --> 00:18:11,642
And so when Michael works on a platform team,

422
00:18:11,962 --> 00:18:14,504
he actually does that for other people,

423
00:18:14,704 --> 00:18:17,585
help them focus on building the game and creative side of it

424
00:18:18,125 --> 00:18:19,966
by taking all of this other stuff away.

425
00:18:20,467 --> 00:18:22,047
And he does that because it aligns

426
00:18:22,107 --> 00:18:25,629
with his own sense of purpose, what gives him fulfillment.

427
00:18:25,989 --> 00:18:27,550
So I don't have to buy him donuts

428
00:18:27,610 --> 00:18:29,651
to convince him to go and work hard on my team.

429
00:18:30,011 --> 00:18:31,412
He does that because he wants to.

430
00:18:32,435 --> 00:18:34,436
So that's the tip number one, start with the why.

431
00:18:34,476 --> 00:18:37,258
Make sure you have very clearly articulated why

432
00:18:37,298 --> 00:18:40,060
for your team, but then make sure that your people

433
00:18:40,580 --> 00:18:43,783
on your team actually align with that sense of why.

434
00:18:43,803 --> 00:18:45,344
So that's number one.

435
00:18:45,784 --> 00:18:48,506
Number two, define success.

436
00:18:49,487 --> 00:18:51,768
A while back my boss gave me a book,

437
00:18:52,769 --> 00:18:55,591
it was called something like On Leadership,

438
00:18:55,631 --> 00:18:57,192
How to Build Successful Organizations,

439
00:18:57,372 --> 00:18:58,453
and it was written by this guy.

440
00:18:58,493 --> 00:18:59,674
How many of you know who this guy is?

441
00:19:00,859 --> 00:19:01,399
Okay, a few.

442
00:19:01,839 --> 00:19:04,242
So this is a basketball coach.

443
00:19:04,422 --> 00:19:05,903
At the time I looked at the book and I'm like,

444
00:19:06,244 --> 00:19:08,065
I don't wanna read this, I'm not into sports,

445
00:19:08,105 --> 00:19:09,647
like why would I even read this?

446
00:19:10,248 --> 00:19:11,148
And so I looked him up.

447
00:19:11,709 --> 00:19:15,212
So this is Coach Wooden of UCLA Basketball.

448
00:19:15,873 --> 00:19:19,737
And this guy, his team won 88.

449
00:19:21,058 --> 00:19:23,360
consecutive games, 88 in a row.

450
00:19:23,380 --> 00:19:25,843
So it's win after win after win after win,

451
00:19:26,203 --> 00:19:27,764
continuously, nonstop.

452
00:19:28,165 --> 00:19:32,089
He won 10 national championships in 12 years,

453
00:19:32,689 --> 00:19:34,091
with a record seven in a row.

454
00:19:34,591 --> 00:19:36,092
Previous record is two in a row.

455
00:19:36,753 --> 00:19:39,656
So if anyone knows about performance, is this guy.

456
00:19:40,582 --> 00:19:42,803
And so, I'm like, okay, I'm gonna read this book.

457
00:19:43,303 --> 00:19:46,005
And in this book, he defines success like this.

458
00:19:46,605 --> 00:19:47,966
So I'm gonna read it, because it's very important.

459
00:19:47,986 --> 00:19:49,646
I know you all can read, but I'm gonna read it anyways.

460
00:19:50,087 --> 00:19:53,248
Success is peace of mind, which is a direct result

461
00:19:53,548 --> 00:19:56,830
of self-satisfaction in knowing you did your best

462
00:19:57,330 --> 00:19:59,271
to become the best you're capable of becoming.

463
00:20:00,231 --> 00:20:03,953
So, understanding this had a profound effect

464
00:20:04,033 --> 00:20:05,354
on how I motivate my teams,

465
00:20:05,434 --> 00:20:07,374
and how I set the goals for them.

466
00:20:08,345 --> 00:20:11,426
it's very easy to set the goals that are like external KPIs

467
00:20:11,886 --> 00:20:13,267
or metrics or targets.

468
00:20:13,747 --> 00:20:17,429
You know, your game must perform to certain Metacritic score

469
00:20:17,669 --> 00:20:19,290
or you must ship by certain date.

470
00:20:20,150 --> 00:20:22,671
When you motivate people by those external kind of outcomes,

471
00:20:23,132 --> 00:20:24,933
they don't necessarily have control over that.

472
00:20:25,113 --> 00:20:28,734
And so it may drive like wrong kind of behaviors.

473
00:20:28,754 --> 00:20:30,335
I don't know if you guys know about,

474
00:20:30,555 --> 00:20:33,657
Wells Fargo recently fired like 5,000 people

475
00:20:34,177 --> 00:20:35,898
because they were creating all these shadow accounts

476
00:20:35,958 --> 00:20:37,278
because their KPI was...

477
00:20:37,759 --> 00:20:40,079
how many accounts they sell in a given time frame.

478
00:20:40,439 --> 00:20:41,780
So you don't want that kind of behavior.

479
00:20:41,840 --> 00:20:44,041
What you want is your teams to continuously

480
00:20:44,081 --> 00:20:47,542
and relentlessly compete against themselves.

481
00:20:47,822 --> 00:20:50,743
One of the probably most weird conversations

482
00:20:50,783 --> 00:20:52,343
I had at Riot when I joined,

483
00:20:53,123 --> 00:20:54,824
when we were talking about releasing some feature,

484
00:20:55,744 --> 00:20:57,505
And I said, well, we should look up

485
00:20:57,565 --> 00:20:58,525
how the competitors do it.

486
00:20:59,085 --> 00:21:00,666
And the guys look at me like, competitors?

487
00:21:01,126 --> 00:21:02,827
We don't compete against people.

488
00:21:03,067 --> 00:21:05,448
We're actually focusing on trying to do the best thing

489
00:21:05,768 --> 00:21:06,888
for the player right now.

490
00:21:07,509 --> 00:21:08,709
And so that just blew my mind.

491
00:21:08,869 --> 00:21:11,110
But that's a really good way to motivate teams

492
00:21:11,510 --> 00:21:13,811
to focus on continuously improving

493
00:21:13,971 --> 00:21:15,032
and competing against themselves.

494
00:21:15,492 --> 00:21:16,412
And so my tip number two.

495
00:21:17,512 --> 00:21:19,613
Tip number three, we talked a little bit about trust.

496
00:21:21,754 --> 00:21:23,475
We all know that there is no high performance

497
00:21:23,495 --> 00:21:24,275
without trust, right?

498
00:21:25,280 --> 00:21:28,442
And in fact, Patrick Linceoni, in his book,

499
00:21:28,862 --> 00:21:30,223
The Five Dysfunctions of a Team,

500
00:21:30,943 --> 00:21:34,325
says that absence of trust is probably the most foundational,

501
00:21:34,345 --> 00:21:35,726
the most common dysfunction on team.

