00:34:51,052 --> 00:34:53,133
about how you can maybe apply those to your teams.

802
00:34:54,553 --> 00:34:57,115
So the first that we noticed was our thriving teams were

803
00:34:57,155 --> 00:35:00,436
really ones that were willing to buy into a decision fully

804
00:35:00,816 --> 00:35:01,717
and then just move on.

805
00:35:02,900 --> 00:35:06,525
So one of the strategies we saw time and time again is people on these teams were willing

806
00:35:06,545 --> 00:35:10,531
to be convinced of different points of view, but more so than that, they would tell each

807
00:35:10,591 --> 00:35:14,216
other specifically what would change their mind, right?

808
00:35:14,297 --> 00:35:18,362
If Garth and I are in a disagreement, it's one thing to acknowledge that I have a particular

809
00:35:18,422 --> 00:35:18,883
viewpoint.

810
00:35:19,184 --> 00:35:21,946
But these teams elevated that and were actually open with

811
00:35:21,986 --> 00:35:24,248
each other about, yeah, I don't agree with you, but

812
00:35:24,288 --> 00:35:26,490
here's some things that would get me to agree with you.

